{All classical international chess events in Mar del Plata and a selection of
tournaments in Buenos Aires are presented.   The tournaments in Mar del Plata
started with South American Chess Championships. Number one had been
Montevideo 1921/22 and won by Roberto Grau. The second, Montevideo 1925, had
Louis Palau as winner. Seventeen players participated in number three, Mar del
Plata (8-30 iii) 1928. Again Argentinians dominated the event.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Bf4 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Nbd2 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O $5 Nh5 8. Bg3 Nxg3 9.
hxg3 f5 10. c4 c6 11. Qc2 Bd6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Rfc1 Nf6 14. Nb3 $5 Ng4 $1 {
Black takes the initiative on the kingside.} 15. Be2 Rf6 $1 16. Nc5 Rh6 17. Nd3
Qe8 18. Ng5 Qg6 19. Nh3 Nxe3 $6 {Grau sacrifices a piece for an attack on the
kingside. He could have developed his queen's bishop.} 20. fxe3 $6 {
White should have postponed this capture.} (20. Qxc8+ $1 Rxc8 21. Rxc8+ Kf7 22.
Ndf4 Qf6 23. fxe3 {gains a material plus.}) 20... Qxg3 21. Kf1 $5 Qxe3 $5 22.
Ndf2 $2 {He misses an effective counteraction.} (22. Qa4 $1 Rf6 23. Rc3 {
leads to chances for both sides.}) 22... Qxd4 {
Grau has won four pawns for a piece.} 23. Rd1 Qh4 24. Qc3 Bd7 25. Qd4 Qxd4 26.
Rxd4 Rc8 27. Nd3 Bc6 28. Rc1 Rd8 29. Nb4 Bxb4 30. Rxb4 e5 $1 {
The pawn avalanche cannot be stopped.} 31. Kf2 Rhd6 32. Rd1 h6 33. Ng1 Kf7 34.
