Kg2 Qg6+ 23. Kh1 Qe4+ {leads to perpetual check.}) 21. Kf2 $1 Bh3 22. Rg1 Ng4+
23. Ke2 $6 (23. Kg3 $1 Nxe3 24. Rde1 Qxc4 25. Rxe3 Qxc3 26. Rxc3 {
wins an exchange.}) 23... Bg2 24. Kd2 $5 Nf2 25. Rde1 Nh3 26. Bd3 Qf3 27. Ref1
$1 Nf2 $1 28. Kc2 Rd8 $1 29. Bc4 $5 Qe4+ 30. Kb3 Rb8+ 31. Ka4 $1 {
The white king is safe for the checks.} c5 $2 ({
Probably, the right order of moves is} 31... Nh3 32. b3 c5) 32. b3 $2 {
He could have captured the knight.} Nh3 33. Rxg2 Qxg2 34. Ka3 Qe4 $2 ({
Correct is} 34... Rd8 $1 35. Qa5 Qd2) 35. Rd1 Qe7 36. Rd5 Nf2 37. Rg5 $2 (37.
Qe5 $1 Qxe5 38. Rxe5 {gains a large positional advantage.}) 37... g6 38. Re5
Qc7 39. Qd2 Ng4 40. Rd5 Nf6 41. Rd6 {The game has become equal. Schwartzman
