{World War II broke out during the Olympiad Buenos Aires 1939. It was hard or
impossible to return home for many players. They hesitated. Seven of them
played a tournament with five Argentinians. It occurred at the Circulo de
Ajedrez from 2 until 19 x 1939.} 1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 Nc6 3. Nbc3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5.
Nxd4 d6 6. Be2 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. h3 d5 10. Nxc6 $5 {
Usually, an exchange is made on d5.} bxc6 11. e5 Ne8 $1 {
Black attacks the advanced pawn.} 12. f4 f6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. O-O Rb8 15. b3
Qc7 16. Bd4 $5 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Qb6 18. Qxb6 axb6 {Equality has been achieved.}
19. g4 $5 Nc7 20. Kh2 Ba6 21. Rae1 Bxe2 22. Rxe2 e6 23. Na4 $5 Kf7 24. Nb2 Ke7
25. Kg3 Kd6 26. a4 b5 $1 27. Rfe1 $6 (27. a5 $6 b4 $1 {
threatens a pawn (Czerniak).}) ({Preferable is} 27. Ra1 $1 bxa4 28. Rxa4) 27...
bxa4 28. Nxa4 Rb4 29. Rf2 c5 30. Nc3 Ra8 31. Rd2 Kc6 $5 32. Re5 Rf8 33. Ne2 Kd6
34. Re3 h6 $1 35. h4 $6 ({Better is} 35. Rd1 Ra8 36. Nc3) 35... h5 $1 36. gxh5
gxh5 37. Re5 Ne8 $1 38. Rd1 ({The pointe is} 38. Rxh5 $2 Nf6 $1 39. Re5 Ne4+)
38... Ng7 39. Rg5 $6 (39. Ra1 $1 Nf5+ 40. Kh3 {defends well.}) 39... Nf5+ 40.
Kh3 $2 {The white position falls apart.} (40. Kf2 $1 c4 41. bxc4 Rxc4 42. c3 {
grabs the last opportunity.}) 40... Re4 $1 41. Rd2 Re3+ 42. Ng3 Nxg3 $5 {
Black could postpone the exchange.} 43. Rxg3 Re4 44. Rg5 Rexf4 45. Rxh5 Rf2 $1
{He is going to win a pawn in the rook ending.} 46. Rd3 $5 R8f3+ 47. Rxf3 Rxf3+
48. Kg4 Rc3 49. Rh8 Rxc2 50. h5 Ke5 51. h6 Rh2 52. Kg3 ({Or} 52. Kg5 Kd4 $1 53.
h7 e5 {and Black wins (Czerniak).}) 52... Rh1 53. h7 Kd4 54. Kg2 Rh6 55. Kg3 e5
56. Kg4 e4 57. Kg5 Rh3 58. Kg6 Rxb3 59. Ra8 Rh3 60. h8=Q+ Rxh8 61. Rxh8 e3 62.
Kf5 Kd3 63. Kf4 e2 {The tournament started with a big surprise.   Najdorf came
