{The twenty-third tournament in Mar del Plata was played from 29 iii until 15
iv 1960. $10,000 came from the lotteries and casinos. Special guests were
Spassky, Fischer, Bronstein and Olafsson. Bobby looked more mature because he
wore tailored suits.} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. h4 g4 5. Ne5 Nf6 6. d4 (
{Preferable is} 6. Bc4 $1 d5 7. exd5 Bd6 {
(Von Heydebrand under der Lasa - Staunton, Brussels 1853).}) 6... d6 7. Nd3
Nxe4 8. Bxf4 Bg7 $5 ({Known is} 8... Qe7) 9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 c5 11. Be2 cxd4
12. O-O $5 {Spassky plays in a true Gambit style.} Nc6 {
Black could have captured on h4.} 13. Bxg4 O-O 14. Bxc8 Rxc8 15. Qg4 f5 16. Qg3
dxc3 17. Rae1 {
White has an attacking position in the central area for two pawns.} Kh8 18. Kh1
$6 {He could have taken pawn d6.} Rg8 19. Bxd6 Bf8 20. Be5+ Nxe5 21. Qxe5+ Rg7
$1 {Pawn h4 falls.} 22. Rxf5 Qxh4+ 23. Kg1 Qg4 $6 (23... Qg3 24. Qxg3 Rxg3 {
leads to a better endgame for Black (Spassky).}) 24. Rf2 Be7 25. Re4 Qg5 $6 (
25... Qd7 $1 26. Rf7 $6 Bc5+ $1 27. Nxc5 Qxf7 28. Ne6 Re8 29. Ng5 Rxe5 30.
Nxf7+ Rxf7 31. Rxe5 Rc7 {keeps the extra pawn in a rook ending.}) 26. Qd4 Rf8
$2 {Bobby blunders a piece.} ({Better is} 26... b6 $1 {(Fischer).}) 27. Re5 $1
Rd8 28. Qe4 Qh4 29. Rf4 {White wins a bishop.   Spassky would defeat Fischer
in this way three times: Bobby achieved an advantage first, but Boris
outwitted him later.} 1-0

